data.title: Extensive menu, great food
data.text: We visited here for lunch during our trip to Arizona. Fabulous menu with lots of choice! Good house wines, we tried a merlot, Cabernet and a Sauvignon, all good and value at $5. We ate the gyros flatbread, a burger sub and the lamb/potato balls. All delicious and very attentive service too. Would highly recommend this place!

data.title: Great food and desserts
data.text: Euro Cafe is an absolute gem.  It's small and tucked in a group of stores, it can be kind of hard to find.  It is one of our favorite places to take friends and guests.  The food is so fresh, lots of variety and the desserts are amazing.  It's definitely worth checking out.

owner_response.author: ChefArizona, Owner at Romeo's Euro Cafe, responded to this review
owner_response.text: Thank you so much for your support. We hope to see you back soon.
owner_response.title: Owner Response

data.title: You must try this place!
data.text: If you want a diverse menu and gastronomic treat, you must try this place.  Their menu is extensive and they have a wonderful wine selection.  It is, however, small and cozy and there may be a bit of a wait.  While waiting, check out their amazing desert collections.

data.title: Love it!
data.text: Good selection of wine and great menu.   The Feta Gyro is amazing and the Monte Cristo!  The staff is great!  Come back again and again.

data.title: Extensive menu
data.text: The Euro Café is hidden away in a multiuser building in the heart of Gilbert. The deco is based on a café style with smaller tables and bent wood backed chairs. The menu is one of the largest in the area with an array from sandwiches to entrees mostly from Mediterranean countries. Although there are no wall or window hangings to soften sounds the atmosphere was quiet. The large menu has a drawback in that not all dishes are of the same quality. The appetizer we chose, an eggplant prosciutto and cheese combination was deep fried and frankly was a bit rank as if the oil needed to be changed. Our entrees on the other hand were delicious. The chicken Veneto and the veal pirata were done perfectly with portions large enough to have leftovers to take home. Overall we were quite pleased and will return.

data.title: OMG!! So GOOD!!!
data.text: Took some friends here for lunch. Holy mackerel!!! The food portions were HUGE and everything is made fresh to order. The desserts are heavenly. Cannot wait to go back!!!!

data.title: Great Mediterranean Food & Desserts
data.text: A large menu with special eggplant, chicken and fish dishes. Broad selection of pasta and pitas. The entree salads are delicious and huge. Likewise the desserts.  Large variety of desserts, maybe 20 or more,  that are very rich. You could easily stop in for dessert.  Service is not fast, but that's due to preparing each dish when it's ordered.  Relax and enjoy some wine with an appetizer.

data.title: Hard to find but worth it!
data.text: I've been going here for years, it gets a little crowded because it's a small space, but we'll worth the cozy atmosphere!  It's Italian and Greek so the menu is large and very diverse. I haven't gotten one thing I didn't enjoy!  Always get the house dressing for your salad, it's delicious!  Also save room for dessert!  The bakery is incredible!

data.title: Relaxed
data.text: Excellent pitas, salads, meals and a nice wine selection. Cozy and comfortable atmosphere...perfect for couples.

data.title: Best Pita Pockets in Town!
data.text: Though Romeo's Euro Cafe boasts an extensive Mediterranean food menu plus excellent dessert and wine selections as well... the pita pocket "gyros" are absolutely fantastic.  Great food at reasonable prices.

data.title: Great Selection
data.text: Lots of great choices on the menu and had the Gyro, which was quite tasty, although a bit on the heavy side with the feta sauce it was still quite good.  They serve both wine and beer and has a nice European cafe feel.  They also have a great variety of deserts to pick from as well.  Nice place to visit when in downtown Gilbert.

data.title: A hidden treasure
data.text: This is food you will want to come back for.  The gyro's are amazing and prepared like someone's grandmother is back in the kitchen. They fry up their own chips that are warm and crunchy. Don't eat too much, the desserts are heaven on a plate. When we have out of town visitors I always take them here and they rave about it. This a cozy small restaurant that is easy to talk, minimal background noise. I have followed Romeo's from it's original location to this one, I am a frequent guest.

data.title: Excellent
data.text:
Great food, gone as a group and everyone liked the food. Have been many times and never had a bad meal. The menu is a little large so it is hard to pick just one thing.
Good portions you won't go away hungry and the deserts are to die for, all made from scratch.

data.title: Favorite Gilbert Restaurant
data.text: Romeo is an excellent chef. We enjoy all of his recipes. All his recipes are done with a Mediterranean flare and the portions are huge. My husband and I often share. The wine is great, the service is great, and the atmosphere is very classy but comfortable. We enjoy the like squares of garlic bread that come with almost all of the entrees and the salads are fresh with homemade dressings. Gilbert's downtown section has really grown with lots of new restaurants but we always come back to Romeo's.

data.title: Eclectic Mediterranean menu
data.text: Great spot in downtown Gilbert. Has been serving excellent distinctive dishes for several years. Many well crafted pita sandwiches. Dinner entrees often large enough to split. Veggie skins are a tasty, popular appetizer. Many unique tastes found here. Mushroom turkey pita and Kasseri chicken are personal favorites.

data.title: Extensive Menu
data.text:
Very extensive menu.  Most like Italian than any other European country.  No German or French food, but LOADS of others.  Lot's of pasta dishes.  Had poultry, and seafood sections as well. Wine of every kind.  I would take my pickier friends there. Have various specials where they match the wine to your entree.  "Quaint" was used very appropriately by another reviewer. Don't expect to see the name on the door. It's on the window next to the door.  Saw a lot of people wondering if they were at the right place.
The food was fantastic.  Spent 3 years in Europe, mainly Italy, and it was as good at Romeo's Euro Cafe as most places across the Pond.

data.title: Wedding party!
data.text:
Romeos has one of the best menu selections around. It takes me forever to decide because there are so many choices. And I have never been disappointed. 
Their dessert counter is fabulous. It certainly lives up to the "Euro" name. Much like the selections in Europe. 
Great little boutique for shopping while you wait. Unique items. I just can never decide if I want the item for myself or as a gift. 
Great little find in Gilbert.

data.title: Nice Quaint Place neatly tucked away in Old Town Gilbert
data.text: Tourist, if you ever want a piece of amazingly decadent dessert, right here. Here it is. You want this place, no other, right here, this is the one. For under $7 a slice, you will be ranting, and raving of how great a place this is (like me) to all your friends. One of Gilbert's best kept secrets. European traveler, this is a must if you are feeling a need for something from home.

data.title: My new favorite place!
data.text:
This place is authentic and cosy and there are a million different things to choose from on the menu. Our waiter was awesome and was very nice and attending as well as gave us advice and suggestions when ordering food and drinks. The food was ABSOLUTELY amazing and takes the visitor to the Mediterranean area in no time.
Definitely my new favorite place in the valley. We will be back!

data.title: I'm the outlier
data.text: I went to Romeo's with a group of twenty. The group as a whole thought the food was very good. I thought it was so-so. Fi9rst, about me. Lived in Long Island 47 years, then in Utah, so I've had great food and very average food.  I'm a serious home cook and I like bold flavors.  I ordered an appetizer of ham cappicola and provolone wrapped in eggplant, battered and deep fried.  I thought it was bland, a the marinara sauce served with it did nothing to elevate it.  For dinner I had the gyro to judge against gyros I've had in other places.  The portion size was very nice and the sauce flavor was pretty good.  But the meat was more in taste and texture like a beef patty from Burger King than nicely spiced slices of gyro meat.  I've had better in Ogden, Utah, hardly the Greek food capital of the world. My other complaint was the wine list- I thought a place with a mid-priced food menu should have some house wines in the $5-6 dollar a glass range- the wines by the glass were mostly $8-10. Maybe I just didn't make the best menu choices, because everyone else was pretty happy, so I'm giving it a 4 rather than a 3.
